ionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Respelling of <i>Caradog</i>, an ancient Celtic name apparently derived from the root <i>cār</i> ‘love’. This name was borne by a British chieftain of the 1st century  ad  in the Latinized form <i>Caractacus</i>, son of Cunobelinos."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Caradog ap Lles Llawddeog was born about 0874, in Wales, his father, Lles Llawddeog, was 25 and his mother, Lles LLawddeog, was 21. He married Tegau Eurfon ferch Llyr in 0893, in Powys, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 0874–":"umbes 0874–Surnud","0870–Male":"0870–Surnud","0874–Male":"0874–Surnud","0890–Male":"0890–Surnud","0876–Female":"0876–Surnud","0900–Male":"0900–Surnud","0910–Male":"0910–Surnud","0920–0962":"0920–0962","0850–0929":"0850–0929","0855–Female":"0855–Surnud","before 0874":"enne 0874","0929":"0929","0890":"0890","0920":"0920","0876":"0876","893":"0893","0962":"0962","0874":"0874","about 0874":"umbes 0874","0850":"0850","about 0910":"umbes 0910","0870":"0870","900":"0900","0855":"0855","0910":"0910","0900":"0900","Europe":"Europe","Wales":"Wales","Powys, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cynric, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Arwystli, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 0874–":"noin 0874–Kuollut","0870–Male":"0870–Kuollut","0874–Male":"0874–Kuollut","0890–Male":"0890–Kuollut","0876–Female":"0876–Kuollut","0900–Male":"0900–Kuollut","0910–Male":"0910–Kuollut","0920–0962":"0920–0962","0850–0929":"0850–0929","0855–Female":"0855–Kuollut","before 0874":"ennen vuotta 0874","0929":"0929","0890":"0890","0920":"0920","0876":"0876","893":"0893","0962":"0962","0874":"0874","about 0874":"noin 0874","0850":"0850","about 0910":"noin 0910","0870":"0870","900":"0900","0855":"0855","0